# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: burmese-sign-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:burmese-sign-language/achang-language] The **Achang language** (Achang: **Ngachang**; Chinese: 阿昌, Burmese: အာချန်) is a Tibeto-Burman language spoken by the Achang (also known as Maingtha and Ngochang) in Yunnan, China, and northern Myanmar.
[src:burmese-sign-language/achang-language] The Xiandao dialect (100 speakers; autonym: *Chintaw* /kʰan³¹tau³¹/) is spoken in the following two locations in Yingjiang County, Dehong Prefecture (*Xiandaoyu Yanjiu*).
[src:burmese-sign-language/achang-language] Voiced sounds /b, d, dz, dʒ, ɟ, ɡ/ can also be heard as voiceless [p, t, ts, tʃ, c, k] in free variation among speakers.
[src:burmese-sign-language/achang-language] /i, ɛ, aˑ/ can also have lax vowel counterparts as [ɪ, æ, ʔaˑ].
[src:burmese-sign-language/achang-language] Achang word order is subject–object–verb.
[src:burmese-sign-language/achang-language] There is no dominant order for nouns and their adjective modifiers.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] For over a decade, the deaf children of the village have attended a boarding school in Mampong-Akuapem, where the ASL based Ghanaian Sign Language is used.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As a consequence, this language has become the first language of these children and their command of AdaSL is decreasing.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This is likely to lead to a complete shift of the deaf community in Adamorobe to Ghanaian Sign Language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As such, AdaSL is an endangered sign language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe is situated approximately 30 to 40 kilometers north of Accra in the Akuapem Hills.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] It is a predominantly Akan village, with the majority of the population speaking the Akan language (Akuapem Twi) in addition to using AdaSL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The community gained attention for its unusually high incidence of hereditary deafness, a phenomenon that has shaped the village's cultural and linguistic landscape.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other deaf communities where deaf individuals are socially marginalized, Adamorobe's deaf residents are fully integrated into village life.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Hearing villagers commonly use AdaSL in daily interactions, creating a bilingual environment that bridges the hearing and deaf worlds seamlessly.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL shares signs and prosodic features with some other sign languages in the region, such as Bura Sign Language, but it has been suggested these similarities are due to culturally shared gestures rather than a genetic relationship.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL has features that set it apart from the sign languages of large deaf communities studied so far, including the absence of the type of classifier construction that expresses motion or location (sometimes called "entity classifiers").
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, AdaSL uses several types of serial verb constructions also found in the surrounding spoken language, Akan.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Nancy Frishberg suggests that AdaSL may be related to the "gestural trade jargon used in the markets throughout West Africa".
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe Sign Language possesses distinct grammatical structures and vocabulary that set it apart from Ghanaian Sign Language and other national or international sign languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many urban sign languages that develop within educational institutions, AdaSL evolved organically within a close-knit community, resulting in unique syntactic constructions and simultaneous sign formations.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Its use is characterized by spatial grammar, classifier constructions, and gestures deeply embedded in the local culture.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The language is not mutually intelligible with GSL, and many signs are specific to Adamorobe's cultural context, making it a rich subject of linguistic study.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL also exhibits a lower reliance on fingerspelling compared to GSL, and it preserves several features that are considered archaic or absent in more standardized sign languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf culture in Adamorobe is notably inclusive.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf residents have historically participated fully in social, economic, and cultural activities.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other societies, deafness in Adamorobe does not carry a stigma.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, sign language has been a natural and respected form of communication, used not only by deaf individuals but also by hearing family members, friends, and neighbors.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This integration is evident in communal gatherings, marketplaces, and traditional ceremonies where sign language is used openly.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The social fabric of Adamorobe has long celebrated this coexistence, which has contributed to the resilience of its deaf community despite external pressures.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL is believed to have emerged over 200 years ago, alongside the settlement's founding.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Genetic studies suggest that the high incidence of deafness in Adamorobe is due to a hereditary mutation passed down through generations.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The earliest academic references to Adamorobe and its sign language date back to the mid-20th century, with researchers noting the community's unique integration of deaf individuals.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] In the 1960s and 1980s, the introduction of formal deaf education in Ghana led to the exposure of Adamorobe's deaf children to Ghanaian Sign Language, which is derived from American Sign Language (ASL).
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This exposure began to shift the linguistic practices of younger generations, who now tend to use GSL more frequently than AdaSL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] A critical turning point in the village's history came in 1975 when the local chief instituted a ban on marriages between deaf individuals in an effort to reduce the incidence of hereditary deafness.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] While this policy effectively decreased the number of deaf births, it also inadvertently threatened the long-term survival of AdaSL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Today, Adamorobe Sign Language faces significant challenges.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The number of deaf individuals in the village has declined due to the marriage policy that discouraged unions between deaf people.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Additionally, the younger generation of deaf children is increasingly adopting Ghanaian Sign Language through formal education, which reduces the intergenerational transmission of AdaSL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The influence of urbanization and national language policies further accelerates the shift away from village sign languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Without deliberate preservation efforts, AdaSL risks becoming endangered or possibly extinct within the next few decades.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Several linguists and anthropologists have documented Adamorobe Sign Language extensively in recent years.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Their efforts aim to preserve the language's unique features and raise awareness of its cultural importance.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] However, there are limited formal initiatives within the village to revitalize or maintain AdaSL among younger generations.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Potential preservation strategies include community-based language programs, the development of AdaSL teaching materials, and the integration of the language into local schools.
[src:burmese-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Encouraging the use of AdaSL in social and cultural events could also contribute to its sustainability.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Myanmar is divided into 21 administrative divisions, which include seven regions, seven states, one union territory, one self-administered division, and five self-administered zones.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The regions were called divisions prior to August 2010, and four of them are named after their capital city, the exceptions being Sagaing Region, Ayeyarwady Region and Tanintharyi Region.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The regions can be described as ethnically predominantly Burman (Bamar), while the states, the zones and Wa Division are dominated by ethnic minorities.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Yangon Region has the largest population and is the most densely populated.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] In terms of land area, Shan State is the largest and Naypyidaw Union Territory is the smallest.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Regions and states are divided into districts (ခရိုင်; *kha yaing* or *khayaing*, IPA: [kʰəjàɪɴ]).
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] These districts consist of townships (မြို့နယ်; *myo-ne*, IPA: [mjo̰nɛ̀]) that include towns (မြို့; *myo*, IPA: [mjo̰]), wards (ရပ်ကွက်; *yatkwet*, IPA: [jaʔ kwɛʔ])) and village tracts (ကျေးရွာအုပ်စု; *kyayywa oksu*, IPA: [tɕé jwà ʔoʊʔ sṵ]).
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Village tracts are groups of adjacent villages (ကျေးရွာ; *kyayywa*, IPA: [tɕé jwà]).
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The self-administered division (SAD) exists at an administrative level half-a-step below that of states, regions and the union territory, and the self-administrative zones (SAZ) exists at the district level.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The self-administered areas were formed by statutes on territory controlled by Myanmar's ethnic armed organisations.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Within the hierarchy, the most significant unit of local governance below the first level is the township which form the a consistent set of administrative units across the country.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Often, local governance will go directly from the township to the ward.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Most of the country do not have separate town offices.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] For example, in 2015, only 7 of the 27 townships of Ayeyarwady Region had a town office at all.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Additionally, some townships are divided into Subtownships (မြို့နယ်ခွဲ), which are semi-official parts of a township administered separately, often revolving around a town separate from the township's principal town.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Many reports will use subtownships, especially more established subtownships used by the main townships themselves.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The administrative structure of the states, regions and self-administering bodies is outlined in the new constitution adopted in 2008.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Executive authority is held in each state or region by a Regional or State Government consisting of a Chief Minister, other ministers and an Advocate General.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The President appoints the Chief Minister from a list of qualified candidates in the regional or state legislature; the legislature must approve this choice unless it is proven that the candidate does not meet constitutional qualifications.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Since 4th March 2026, the Region or State minister responsible for development affairs is appointed as the mayor for the capital of the respective Region or State.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Legislative authority resides with the State Hluttaw or Region Hluttaw made up of elected civilian members and representatives of the Armed Forces.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Both divisions are considered equivalent, the only distinction being that states have large ethnic minority populations and regions are mostly populated by the national majority Burmans / Bamar.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The constitution states that Naypyidaw shall be a Union Territory under the direct administration of the President.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Day-to-day functions would be carried out on the President's behalf by the Naypyidaw Council led by a Chairperson.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The Chairperson and members of the Naypyidaw Council are appointed by the President and shall include civilians and representatives of the Armed Forces.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Self-Administered Zones and Self-Administered Divisions are administered by a Leading Body.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The Leading Body consists of at least ten members and includes State or Regional Hluttaw members elected from the Zones or Divisions and other members nominated by the Armed Forces.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The Leading Body has both executive and legislative powers.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] A Chairperson is head of each Leading Body.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Districts are the second-order divisions of Myanmar and are often named after a population center within the district of the same name.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Shan State has the most districts, even excluding Self-Administered Zones and Divisions.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Naypyidaw Union Territory, Tanintharyi and Mon State have the least with just 4 districts.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The District's role is more supervisory as the 330 townships are the basic administrative unit of local governance and are the only type of administrative division that covers the entirety of Myanmar.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] A District is led by a District Administrator and a Township is administered by a Township Administrator.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Both are appointed civil servants through the General Administration Department (GAD) of the Ministry of Home Affairs (MOHA).
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The Minister of Home Affairs is to be appointed by the military according to the 2008 constitution.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The 2008 Constitution of Myanmar defined 75 districts.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] In April 2022, 46 additional districts were formed by MOHA bringing the total up to 121 districts.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Most local governance services are offered at the Township level; few services are offered at the District level.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The Township Administrator is the key focal point for most interactions with the government and the Township Administrator serves as a representative of the State or Region government and executes functions on behalf of the State or Region.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] All Township governments are staffed by 34 GAD civil servants regardless of population, although larger townships may have several Township committees that coordinate with the Township and report to the District.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Subtownships exist for many but not all townships.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] They can be created for many reasons including, townships with large areas, townships with a large natural barrier or townships with a lopsided population distribution.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] These subtownships are unofficial, but can be used by the Township administration and national ministries for data collection and administrative ease.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The lowest level of practical administration is the ward for urban areas and village for rural areas.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Villages are grouped into and administered as village tracts.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Village Tracts may contain up to 8 distinct villages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Some townships include areas not part of any ward or village tract.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Most townships contain at least one ward/town, and are usually named after the population center.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] As of reforms in 2012 and 2013, Ward and Village Tract administrators are now typically elected, but report to the appointed Township Administrator.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Ward Administrators and Village Tract Administrators (also called just Village Administrators) are supported by 100-household-heads and 10-household-heads who are collectively called area leaders.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Most cities in Myanmar are contained within one township like Pathein.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] In some cases, the rural portions of the township may be administered semi-independently as sub-townships.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] In Mandalay, the municipality was functionally administered at the Mandalay District level with townships acting de facto as subdivisions of a city prior to 2022.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] In Yangon, the administrative jurisdiction of the Yangon City Development Committee overlap across 33 townships and all 4 of Yangon Region's pre-2022 districts.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The definition of a city is ambiguous with the Burmese term မြို့ ('myo') being translated as any urban area.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The General Administration Department only explicitly defines the three cities of Yangon, Mandalay and Naypyidaw.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] On 10 October 1922, the Karenni States of Bawlake, Kantarawaddy, and Kyebogyi became a part of the Federated Shan States.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] In 1940, Minbu division's name was changed to Magwe, and Meiktila Divisions became part of Mandalay District.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Upon independence, on 4 January 1948, the Chin Hills area was split from Arakan Division to form Chin Special Division, and Kachin State was formed by carving out the Myitkyina and Bhamo districts of Mandalay Division.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Karen State was also created from Amherst, Thaton, and Toungoo Districts of Tenasserim Division.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Mongpai State of the Federated Shan States was separated to form Karenni State, and Shan State was formed by merging the other Federated Shan States and the Wa States.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] In 1952, Karenni State was renamed Kayah State.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] In 1964, Rangoon Division was separated from Pegu Division, whose capital shifted to Pegu.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] In addition, Karen State was renamed Kawthoolei State.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] In 1972, the Hanthawaddy and Hmawbi districts were moved under Rangoon Division's jurisdiction.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] In 1974, after Ne Win introduced a constitution, Chin Special Division became a state, and its capital moved from Falam to Hakha.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Kawthoolei State's name was reverted to Karen State.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Mon State was created out of portions of Tenasserim Division and Pegu Division.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] Mon State's capital became Moulmein, and Tenasserim Division's became Tavoy.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] In addition, Arakan Division was granted statehood.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] In 1989, after the coup d'état by the military junta, the names of many divisions in Burma were altered in English to reflect Burmese pronunciations.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] After 1995, in Kachin State Mohnyin District was created out of Myitkyina District as part of the peace agreement with the Kachin Independence Army.
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] The 2008 Constitution stipulates the renaming of the 7 "divisions" (တိုင်း in Burmese) as "regions" (တိုင်းဒေသကြီး in Burmese).
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] It also stipulates the creation of Union territories, which include the capital of Nay Pyi Taw and ethnic self-administered zones (ကိုယ်ပိုင်အုပ်ချုပ်ခွင့်ရဒေသ in Burmese) and self-administered divisions (ကိုယ်ပိုင်အုပ်ချုပ်ခွင့်ရတိုင်း in Burmese).
[src:burmese-sign-language/administrative-divisions-of-myanmar] On 20 August 2010, the renaming of the 7 divisions and the naming of the 6 self-administered zones was announced by Burmese state media.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] American Sign Language (ASL) has grammar just like any other sign language or spoken language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The study of ASL structure dates back to William Stokoe, Dorothy Casterline, and Carl Croneberg in the 1960s.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Since then, linguists have been describing patterns in ASL responsible for creating meaning at all kinds of levels, from the word, to phrases and sentences and beyond.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all of these linguists ascribe to the same theoretical framework, using various theories, models, and analyses.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some analyze the language from a generative linguistics perspective, while others from a cognitive linguistics perspective.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL morphology, publications have historically categorized morphological processes under two umbrellas: derivational morphology and inflectional morphology.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Derivational morphology is the process by which new units can be created in a language, and like any other language, this process has been observed in a variety of forms in ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One form of derivational morphology occurs when a change in movement changes the sign's meaning – often between a noun and a verb.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This may be done either by reduplicating the movement of the verb if the verb has a single movement, or by restraining (making smaller and faster) the movement of the verb if it already has repeated movement.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the noun CHAIR is derived from the verb SIT through reduplication.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way of deriving new words in ASL is via the process of compounding, which often differ in meaning from their constituent signs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the signs FACE and STRONG compound to create a new sign FACE^STRONG, meaning 'to resemble'.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed various compounds as a type of suffixation.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Agent nouns may be derived from verbs by adding the sign, or suffix, AGENT and deleting the final hold of the verb, e.g.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Superlatives have also been analyzed as created by a formed by suffixation, e.g.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, Ted Supalla's work on ASL verbs of motion analyzed these signs as consisting of many different affixes, articulated simultaneously according to complex grammatical constraints.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This differs from the concatenative morphology of many spoken languages, which except for suprasegmental features, such as tone, are tightly constrained by the sequential nature of voice sounds.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation is another derivational morphological process that has been studied in ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Certain types of signs, for example, those relating to time and age, may incorporate numbers by assimilating their handshape.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the word for 'week' has handshape /B/ with the weak hand and /1/ with the active hand; the active hand's handshape may be changed to the handshape of any number up to 9 to indicate that many weeks.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed this phenomenon as a type of affixation.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Signs of age, for example, will begin with a touch at the chin.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They argue that this touch functions as a prefix which completely assimilates with the handshape of the corresponding age number.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For instance, the word for 'nine' is signed with an /F/ handshape produced ipsilaterally in front of the signer's shoulder.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The chin-touch in 'nine years old' can be analyzed as an affix, which is then produced with this same /F/ handshape.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'three years old', however, the prefix is made with a 3 handshape.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Inflectional morphology adds units of language to other words.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, this would be changing 'watch' to 'watches' or 'watching.' In ASL, the sign may remain unchanged as WATCH, or the meaning may change based on non-manual markers (NMM).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL morphology demonstrates reduplication and indexicality as well.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are about 20 non-manual modifiers in ASL, which are either adjectival or adverbial.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rather than relying on sequential affixes, ASL makes heavy use of simultaneous modification of signs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One example of this is found in the aspectual system (see below); another is *numeral incorporation:* There are several families of two-handed signs which require one of the hands to take the handshape of a numeral.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, drawing the dominant hand lengthwise across the palm and fingers of a flat B hand indicates a number of weeks; the dominant hand takes the form of a numeral from one to nine to specify how many weeks.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are analogous signs for 'weeks ago' and 'weeks from now', etc., though in practice several of these signs are only found with the lower numerals.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL also has a system of classifiers which may be incorporated into signs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These classifiers are moved through sign space to iconically represent the actions of their referents.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, an ILY hand may 'lift off' or 'land on' a horizontal B hand to sign an aircraft taking off or landing; a 3 hand may be brought down on a B hand to sign parking a car; and a G hand may be brought toward a V hand to represent one person approaching two.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The frequency of classifier use depends greatly on genre, occurring at a rate of 17.7% in narratives but only 1.1% in casual speech and 0.9% in formal speech.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Frames are a morphological device that may be unique to sign languages (Liddell 2004).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are incomplete sets of the features which make up signs, and they combine with existing signs, absorbing features from them to form a derived sign.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is the frame which specifies the number and nature of segments in the resulting sign, while the basic signs it combines with lose all but one or two of their original features.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One, the WEEKLY frame, consists of a simple downward movement.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It combines with the signs for the days of the week, which then lose their inherent movement.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'Monday' consists of an M/O hand made with a circling movement.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'MondayWEEKLY' (that is, 'on Mondays') is therefore signed as an M/O hand that drops downward, but without the circling movement.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A similar ALL DAY frame (a sideward pan) combines with times of the day, such as 'morning' and 'afternoon', which likewise keep their handshape and location but lose their original movement.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation (see above) also uses frames.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, in ASL frames are most productively utilized for verbal aspect.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] While there is no grammatical tense in ASL, there are numerous verbal aspects.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are produced by modulating the verb: through reduplication, by placing the verb in an aspectual frame (see above), or with a combination of these means.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] An example of an aspectual frame is the *unrealized inceptive* aspect ('just about to X'), illustrated here with the verb 'to tell'.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'To tell' is an indexical (directional) verb, where the index finger (a G hand) begins with a touch to the chin and then moves outward to point out the recipient of the telling.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The handshape throughout the sign is whichever is required by the final hold, in this case a G hand.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The variety of aspects in ASL can be illustrated by the verb 'to be sick', which involves the middle finger of the Y/8 hand touching the forehead, and which can be modified by a large number of frames.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Several of these involve reduplication, which may but need not be analyzed as part of the frame.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These modulations readily combine with each other to create yet finer distinctions.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all verbs take all aspects, and the forms they do take will not necessarily be completely analogous to the verb illustrated here.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Conversely, not all aspects are possible with this one verb.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect is unusual in ASL in that transitive verbs derived for aspect lose their transitivity.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Reduplication is also used for expressing verbal number.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Verbal number indicates that the action of the verb is repeated; in the case of ASL it is apparently limited to transitive verbs, where the motion of the verb is either extended or repeated to cover multiple object or recipient loci.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] (Simple plurality of action can also be conveyed with reduplication, but without indexing any object loci; in fact, such aspectual forms do not allow objects, as noted above.) There are specific dual forms (and for some signers trial forms), as well as plurals.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the singular verb uses reduplication, that is lost in the dual and plural forms.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of personal name signs in ASL: fingerspelled, arbitrary, and descriptive.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Fingerspelled names are simply spelled out letter-by-letter.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs only refer to a person's name, while descriptive name signs refer to a person's personality or physical characteristics.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Once given, names are for life, apart from changing from one of the latter types to an arbitrary sign in childhood.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are usually assigned by another member of the Deaf community, and signal inclusion in that community.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are not used to address people, as names are in English, but are used only for third-person reference, and usually only when the person is absent.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The majority of people, probably well in excess of 90%, have arbitrary name signs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are initialized signs: The handshape is the initial of one of the English names of the person, usually the first.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign may occur in neutral space, with a tremble; with a double-tap (as a noun) at one of a limited number of specific locations, such as the side of the chin, the temple, or the elbow; or moving across a location or between two locations, with a single tap at each.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Single-location signs are simpler in connotation, like English "Vee"; double-location signs are fancier, like English "Veronica".
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sam Supalla (1992) collected 525 simple arbitrary name signs like these.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two constraints on arbitrary signs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, it should not duplicate an existing ASL word.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Second, there should not be more than one person with the name sign in the local community.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person moves to a new community where someone already has their name sign, then the newcomer is obligated to modify theirs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is usually accomplished by compounding the handshape, so that the first tap of the sign takes the initial of the person's first English name, and the second tap takes the initial of their last name.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are potentially thousands of such compound-initial signs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs are not initialized, but rather use non-core ASL signs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They tend to be assigned and used by children, rather like "Blinky" in English.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Parents do not give such names to their children, but most Deaf people do not have deaf parents and are assigned their name sign by classmates in their first school for the deaf.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] At most 10% of Deaf people retain such name signs into adulthood..
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs became established very early in the history of ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs refer to a person's appearance or personality.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The two systems, arbitrary and descriptive, are sometimes combined, usually for humorous purposes.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Hearing people learning ASL are also often assigned combined name signs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is not traditional for Deaf people.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sometimes people with very short English names, such as "Ann" or "Lee", or ones that flow easily, such as "Larry", may never acquire a name sign, but may instead be referred to with finger-spelling.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-Manual Markers (NMM), or Non-Manual Signals (NMS) are communication methods not found in the hands.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They typically consist of facial expressions and body language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs can change the grammar of a sentence.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not every sign uses non-manual markers, but for many others, these markers determine what sign is being produced.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some examples of non-manual markers would be the shifting of shoulders, the lowering or raising of eyebrows, a head nod or shake, scrunching of the nose, pursing of the lips, or an open mouth.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs are important for indicating if a question is being asked.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For *WH-* questions, the eyebrows are lowered, and for *YES/NO* questions, the eyebrows are raised.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is hard to indicate if a question is being asked otherwise without facial indicators.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another example would be between *I UNDERSTAND* and *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign for this is the same; the hand is held up near the forehead with the palm facing the self.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the person is nodding and has their eyebrows raised, it means *I UNDERSTAND*.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If they are shaking their head with eyebrows lowered, it means *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Understanding ASL grammar requires understanding the difference between a signer's dominant and non-dominant hand.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person is right-handed, then their right hand is their dominant hand, and their left hand is their non-dominant hand.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Almost all signs are completed with the more active, dominant hand, while the non-dominant hand serves as a base.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For signs requiring two hands, the dominant hand performs more of the active component.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a subject–verb–object (SVO) language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, OSV is also an accepted sentence form.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The default SVO word order is sometimes altered by processes including topicalization and null elements.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is marked either with non-manual signals like eyebrow or body position, or with prosodic marking such as pausing.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These non-manual grammatical markings (such as eyebrow movement or head-shaking) may optionally spread over the c-command domain of the node which it is attached to.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, ASL is a pro-drop language, and when the manual sign that a non-manual grammatical marking is attached to is omitted, the non-manual marking obligatorily spreads over the c-command domain.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The full sentence structure in ASL is [topic] [subject] verb [object] [subject–pronoun–tag].
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics and *tags* are both indicated with non-manual features, and both give a great deal of flexibility to ASL word order.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within a noun phrase, the word order is noun–number and noun–adjective.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL does not have a copula (linking 'to be' verb).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition to its basic topic–comment structure, ASL typically places an adjective after a noun, though it may occur before the noun for stylistic purposes.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numerals also occur after the noun, a very rare pattern among oral languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Adverbs, however, occur before the verbs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Most of the time adverbs are simply the same sign as an adjective, distinguished by the context of the sentence.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] When the scope of the adverb is the entire clause, as in the case of time, it comes before the topic.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL makes heavy use of time-sequenced ordering, meaning that events are signed in the order in which they occur.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, for *I was late to class last night because my boss handed me a huge stack of work after lunch yesterday,* one would sign 'YESTERDAY LUNCH FINISH, BOSS GIVE-me WORK BIG-STACK, NIGHT CLASS LATE-me'.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In stories, however, ordering is malleable, since one can choose to sequence the events either in the order in which they occurred or in the order in which one found out about them.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has been claimed that tense in ASL is marked adverbially, and that ASL lacks a separate category of tense markers.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] (1992, 1995) argue that "Tense" (T) is indeed a distinct category of syntactic head, and that the T node can be occupied either by a modal (e.g.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect may be marked either by verbal inflection or by separate lexical items.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As noted above, in ASL aspectually marked verbs cannot take objects.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] To deal with this, the object must be known from context so that it does not need to be further specified.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It may be used as the topic of the utterance at hand.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Of these two strategies, the first is the more common.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic sets off background information that will be discussed in the following main clause.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topicalization is used productively in ASL and often results in surface forms that do not follow the basic SVO word order.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In order to non-manually mark topics, the eyebrows are raised and the head is tilted back during the production of a topic.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The head is often lowered toward the end of the sign, and sometimes the sign is followed rapidly nodding the head.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way topics may be signed is by shifting the body.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The signer may use the space on one side of his/her body to sign the topic, and then shifts to the other side for the rest of the sentence.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL utterances do not require topics, but their use is extremely common.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are used for purposes of information flow, to set up referent loci (see above), and to supply objects for verbs which are grammatically prevented from taking objects themselves (see below).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, people tend to want to set up the object of their concern first and then discuss what happened to it.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of non-manual topic markers, all of which involve raised eyebrows.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The three types of non-manual topic markers are used with different types of topics and in different contexts, and the topic markings cannot spread over other elements in the utterance.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics can be moved from and remain null in the main clause of an utterance, or topics can be base-generated and either be co-referential to either the subject or object in the main clause or be related to the subject of object by a semantic property.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The first type of non-manual marking, topic marking 1 (tm1), is only used with a moved topic.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm1 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and head tilted backwards.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] At the end of the sign the head moves down and there is a pause, often with an eye blink, before the sentence is continued.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topic marking 2 (tm2) and topic marking 3 (tm3) are both used with base-generated topics.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and the head tilted backwards and to the side.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Toward the end of the sign the head moves forward and to the opposite side, and there is a pause and often an eye blink before continuing.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For tm3 the eyebrows are raised and the eyes are opened wide, the head starts tilted down and jerks up and down, the lips are opened and raised, and the head is nodded rapidly a few times before pausing and continuing the sentence.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Although both tm2 and tm3 accompany base-generated topics, they are used in different contexts.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is used to introduce new information and change the topic of a conversation to something that the signer is going to subsequently characterize, while tm3 is used to introduce new information that the signer believes is already known by his/her interlocutor.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 may be used with any base-generated topic, whereas only topics that are co-referential with an argument in the sentence may be marked with tm3.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL sentences may have up to two marked topics.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Possible combinations of topic types are two tm2 topics, two tm3 topics, tm2 preceding tm1, tm3 preceding tm1, and tm2 preceding tm3.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sentences with these topic combinations in the opposite orders or with two tm1 topics are considered ungrammatical by native signers.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Relative clauses are signaled by tilting back the head and raising the eyebrows and upper lip.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is done during the performance of the entire clause.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] where the brackets here indicate the duration of the non-manual features.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the sign 'recently' were made without these features, it would lie outside the relative clause, and the meaning would change to "the dog which chased the cat recently came home".
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Negated clauses may be signaled by shaking the head during the entire clause.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic, however, cannot be so negated; the headshake can only be produced during the production of the main clause.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, in many communities, negation is put at the end of the clause, unless there is a wh- question word.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the sentence, "I thought the movie was not good," could be signed as, "BEFORE MOVIE ME SEE, THINK WHAT?
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two manual signs that negate a sentence, NOT and NONE, which are accompanied by a shake of the head.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of questions with different constructions in ASL: wh- questions, yes/no questions, and rhetorical questions.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are grammatical and semantic features that do not include the use of hands.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They can include mouth shape, eye gazes, facial expressions, body shifting, head tilting, and eyebrow raising.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings can also aid in identifying sentence type, which is especially relevant to our discussion of different types of interrogatives.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Wh-questions can be formed in a variety of ways in ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The wh-word can appear solely at the end of the sentence, solely at the beginning of the sentence, at both the beginning and end of the sentence (see section 4.4.2.1 on 'double-occurring wh-words', or in situ (i.e. where the wh-word is in the sentence structure before movement occurs)).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Manual wh-signs are also accompanied by a non-manual grammatical marking (see section 4.4.1), which can include a variety of features.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This non-manual grammatical marking can spread optionally over the entire wh-phrase or just a small part.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some languages have very few wh-words, where context and discourse are sufficient to elicit the information that one needs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL has many different wh-words, with certain wh-words having multiple variations.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A list of the wh-words of ASL can be found below.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As mentioned above, ASL possesses wh-questions with word initial placement, word final placement, in situ structure, but the most unique style of wh-word occurrence in ASL is where the wh-word occurs twice, copied in final position.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling can be seen in the table below.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling provides a useful template to analyze two separate analyses about whether wh-words move rightward or leftward in ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] While some researchers argue for rightward movement in wh- questions such as Aarons and Neidle, others, including Petronio and Lillo-Martin, have argued that ASL has leftward movement and wh- words that appear to the right of the clause move by other processes.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both analyses agree upon the fact that there is wh-movement present in these interrogative phrases, but it is a matter of what direction the wh-movement is moving in that causes controversy.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis is congruent with cross-linguistic data that wh-movement is always leftward.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It can be seen as the less controversial of the two proposals.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments presented by the Leftward Wh-movement analysis are: That the spec-CP is on the left, that the wh-movement is leftward, and that the final wh-word in a sentence is a base-generated double.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is illustrated in the syntax tree located to the right of this paragraph.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arguments for leftward movement are based on the facts that if wh-movement in ASL were rightward, ASL would be an exception to cross-linguistic generalizations that wh-movement is leftward.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has also been hypothesized that wh-elements cannot be topicalized, as topicalized elements must be presupposed and interrogatives are not.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This would be detrimental to the rightward analysis, as they are analyzing the doubled wh-word as a 'base generated topic'.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The rightward movement analysis is a newer, more abstract argument of how wh-movement occurs in ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments for rightward movement begin by analyzing spec-CP as being on the right, the wh-movement as being rightward, and as the initial wh-word as a base-generated topic.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This can be seen in the syntax tree on the right.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One of the rightward movement analysis' main arguments is in regards to the non-manual grammatical markings, and their optional spreading over the sentence.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL the use of non-manual grammatical markings is optional depending on the type of wh-question being asked.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the rightward analysis both partial and full spreading of non-manual grammatical markers can be accounted for due to the association with the +WH feature over its c-command domain.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the leftward analysis, the partial or full spreading of non manual grammatical markings cannot be accounted for in this same way.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis requires wh-marking to extend over the entirety of the question, regardless (which is not what is attested in ASL).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In spoken language Yes/no questions will oftentimes differ in their word order from the statement form.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL, yes/no questions are marked by the non-manual grammatical markings (as discussed in section 4.4.1).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This eyebrow raise, slight tilt of the head and lean forward are what indicate that a yes/no question is being asked, without any change in word order from the statement form.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is speculation amongst linguists that these non-manual grammatical markings that indicate a yes/no questions are similar to the question intonation of spoken languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Yes/no questions differ from wh-questions as they do not differ in word order from the original statement form of the sentence, whereas wh-questions do.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As well, in yes/no questions, the non-manual marking must be used over the whole utterance in order for it to be judged as a statement opposed to a question.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The yes/no question is the same word order as the statement form of the sentence, with the addition of non-manual grammatical markings.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are also used for rhetorical questions, which are questions that do not intend to elicit an answer.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] To distinguish the non-manual marking for rhetorical questions from that of yes/no questions, the body is in a neutral position opposed to tilted forward, and the head is tilted in a different way than in yes/no questions.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rhetorical questions are much more common in ASL than in English.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] [I LIKE]NEGATIVE [WHAT?]RHETORICAL, GARLIC.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This strategy is commonly used instead of signing the word 'because' for clarity or emphasis.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] PASTA I EAT ENJOY TRUE [WHY?]RHETORICAL, ITALIAN I.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL signers set up regions of space (loci) for specific referents (see above); these can then be referred to indexically by pointing at those locations with pronouns and indexical verbs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, they point to their referent, or to a locus representing their referent.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the referent is not physically present, the speaker identifies the referent and then points to a location (the *locus)* in the sign space near their body.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This locus can then be pointed at to refer to the referent.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Theoretically, any number of loci may be set up, as long as the signer and recipient remember them all, but in practice, no more than eight loci are used.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier 1990 demonstrates that only two grammatical persons are distinguished in ASL: First person and non-first person, as in Damin.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both persons come in several numbers as well as with signs such as 'my' and 'by myself'.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier provides several arguments for believing that ASL does not formally distinguish second from third person.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, when pointing to a person that is physically present, a pronoun is equivalent to either 'you' or '(s)he' depending on the discourse.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is nothing in the sign itself, nor in the direction of eye gaze or body posture, that can be relied on to make this distinction.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, the same formal sign can refer to any of several second or third persons, which the indexic nature of the pronoun makes clear.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In English, indexic uses also occur, as in 'I need *you* to go to the store and *you* to stay here', but not so ubiquitously.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In contrast, several first-person ASL pronouns, such as the plural possessive ('our'), look different from their non-first-person equivalents, and a couple of pronouns do not occur in the first person at all, so first and non-first persons are formally distinct.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Personal pronouns have separate forms for singular ('I' and 'you/(s)he') and plural ('we' and 'you/they').
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These have possessive counterparts: 'my', 'our', 'your/his/her', 'your/their'.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, there are pronoun forms which incorporate numerals from two to five ('the three of us', 'the four of you/them', etc.), though the dual pronouns are slightly idiosyncratic in form *(i.e.,* they have a K rather than 2 handshape, and the wrist nods rather than circles).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These numeral-incorporated pronouns have no possessive equivalents.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Also among the personal pronouns are the 'self' forms ('by myself', 'by your/themselves', etc.).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These only occur in the singular and plural (there is no numeral incorporation), and are only found as subjects.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They have derived emphatic and 'characterizing' forms, with modifications used for derivation rather like those for verbal aspect.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The 'characterizing' pronoun is used when describing someone who has just been mentioned.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It only occurs as a non-first-person singular form.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Finally, there are formal pronouns used for honored guests.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These occur as singular and plural in the non-first person, but only as singular in the first person.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a pro-drop language, which means that pronouns are not used when the referent is obvious from context and is not being emphasized.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within ASL there is a class of indexical (often called 'directional') verbs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These include the signs for 'see', 'pay', 'give', 'show', 'invite', 'help', 'send', 'bite', etc.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These verbs include an element of motion that indexes one or more referents, either physically present or set up through the referent locus system.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If there are two loci, the first indicates the subject and the second the object, direct or indirect depending on the verb, reflecting the basic word order of ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'give' is a bi-indexical verb based on a flattened M/O handshape.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'I give you', the hand moves from myself toward you; for 'you give me', it moves from you to me.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The verb 'to be in pain' (index fingers pointed at each other and alternately approaching and separating) is signed at the location of the pain (head for headache, cheek for toothache, abdomen for stomachache, etc.).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is normally done in relation to the signer's own body, regardless of the person feeling the pain, but may take also use the locus system, especially for body parts which are not normally part of the sign space, such as the leg.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are also spatial verbs such as put-up and put-below, which allow signers to specify where things are or how they moved them around.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-phabet] Like SignFont and Stokoe notation, ASL-phabet is a phonemic script, but it has been simplified to the point where there is some ambiguity, that is, one symbol can represent more than one phonemic element (handshape, location or movement).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-phabet] For example, whereas SignFont has 25 letters encoding types of movement, and Stokoe notation has 24, ASL-phabet has just 5.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-phabet] This can result in homographs (more than one sign spelled the same way).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-phabet] All together, ASL-phabet has 22 letters for handshape, 5 for location, and 5 for movement.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-phabet] They are written in that order, left-to-right, with the possibility for several letters of each type, such as two handshape letters for a two-handed sign.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-phabet] Like Stokoe notation (but unlike SignFont), the ASL-phabet does not provide symbols for facial expressions, mouthing, and other aspects of sign language structure, which may make it hard to use for extended text.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl-phabet] However, it is sufficient to look up ASL words in an ASL–English dictionary.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL originated in the early 19th century in the American School for the Deaf in Hartford, Connecticut, from a situation of language contact.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Since then, ASL use has been propagated widely by schools for the deaf and deaf community organizations.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Despite its wide use, no accurate count of ASL users has been taken.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Reliable estimates for American ASL users range from 250,000 to 500,000 persons, including a number of children of deaf adults (CODA) and other hearing individuals.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Signs in ASL have a number of phonemic components, such as movement of the face, the torso, shoulders, and the hands.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL is not a form of pantomime, although iconicity plays a larger role in ASL than in spoken languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] English loan words are often borrowed through fingerspelling, although ASL grammar is unrelated to that of English.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL has verbal agreement and aspectual marking and has a productive system of forming agglutinative classifiers.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Many linguists believe ASL to be a subject–verb–object language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] However, there are several other proposals to account for ASL word order .
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL emerged as a language at the American School for the Deaf, co-founded by Thomas Gallaudet and Laurent Clerc in 1817, which brought together Old French Sign Language, several indigenous sign languages, Martha's Vineyard sign language, and various home sign systems.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL was created in that situation by language contact.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL is influenced by its forerunners, yet linguistically distinct.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The influence of French Sign Language (LSF) on ASL is readily apparent; for example, it has been found that about 58% of signs in modern ASL are cognates to Old French Sign Language signs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] However, that is far less than the standard 80% measure used to determine whether related languages are actually dialects.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] That suggests nascent ASL was highly affected by the other signing systems brought by the ASD students although the school's original director, Laurent Clerc, taught in LSF.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] It has been proposed that ASL is a creole in which LSF is the superstrate language and the native indigenous sign languages are substrate languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] However, more recent research has shown that modern ASL does not share many of the structural features that characterize creole languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL may have begun as a creole and then undergone structural change over time, but it is also possible that it was never a creole-type language to begin with.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] There are modality-specific reasons that signed languages tend towards agglutination, such as the ability to simultaneously convey information via the face, head, torso, and other body parts.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] That might override creole characteristics such as the tendency towards isolating morphology.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Additionally, Laurent Clerc and Thomas Hopkins Gallaudet may have used an artificially constructed form of manually coded language in instruction rather than true LSF.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Although the United States, the United Kingdom, and Australia share English as a common oral and written language, ASL is not mutually intelligible with either British Sign Language (BSL) or Auslan.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] All three languages show degrees of borrowing from English, but that alone is not sufficient for cross-language comprehension.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] However, that does not seem justified historically for ASL and Auslan, and it is likely that the resemblance is caused by the higher degree of iconicity in sign languages in general as well as contact with English.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] American Sign Language is growing in popularity in many states.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Many high school and university students desire to take it as a foreign language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] This increased interest is also reflected beyond education, with ASL appearing more frequently in mainstream media through adaptations in film and popular media.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL has also gained greater public visibility through social media and online platforms, where deaf and hard-of-hearing users share educational content and resources for learning the language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Research on video-sharing platforms such as TikTok has found that there are opportunities for ASL users to create and distribute sign language content to wider audiences.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL users, however, have a very distinct culture.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Their facial expressions and hand movements reflect what they are communicating.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] They also have their own sentence structure, which sets the language apart from other spoken and signed languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL allows information to be expressed spatially, with meaning that is conveyed through the placement and movement of signs in relation to one another rather than through a strictly linear sequence.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] American Sign Language is now being accepted by many colleges as a language eligible for foreign language course credit; many states are making it mandatory to accept it as such.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In some states however, this is only true with regard to high school coursework.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Organizations such as the American Sign Language Teachers Association support ASL education by providing professional development, certification and networking opportunities for teachers of ASL and Deaf Studies.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Prior to the birth of ASL, sign language had been used by various communities in the United States.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In the United States, as elsewhere in the world, hearing families with deaf children have historically employed ad hoc home sign, which often reaches much higher levels of sophistication than gestures used by hearing people in spoken conversation.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] As early as 1541 at first contact by Francisco Vásquez de Coronado, there were reports that the Indigenous peoples of the Great Plains widely spoke a sign language to communicate across vast national and linguistic lines.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In the 19th century, a "triangle" of indigenous sign languages developed in New England: one in Martha's Vineyard, Massachusetts; one in Henniker, New Hampshire, and one in Sandy River Valley, Maine.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Martha's Vineyard Sign Language (MVSL), which was particularly important for the history of ASL, was used mainly in Chilmark, Massachusetts.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Due to intermarriage in the original community of English settlers of the 1690s, and the recessive nature of genetic deafness, Chilmark had a high 4% rate of genetic deafness.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] MVSL was used even by hearing residents whenever a deaf person was present, and also in some situations where spoken language would be ineffective or inappropriate, such as during church sermons or between boats at sea.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL is thought to have originated in the American School for the Deaf, founded in Hartford, Connecticut, in 1817.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Originally known as *The American Asylum, At Hartford, For The Education And Instruction Of The Deaf And Dumb*, the school was founded by the Yale graduate and divinity student Thomas Hopkins Gallaudet.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Gallaudet, inspired by his success in demonstrating the learning abilities of a young deaf girl Alice Cogswell, traveled to Europe in order to learn deaf pedagogy from European institutions.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Ultimately, Gallaudet chose to adopt the methods of the French Institut National de Jeunes Sourds de Paris, and convinced Laurent Clerc, an assistant to the school's founder Charles-Michel de l'Épée, to accompany him back to the United States.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Upon his return, Gallaudet and Clerc founded the ASD on April 15, 1817.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In 2019, April 15 was declared as the National American Sign Language Day.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The largest group of students during the first seven decades of the school were from Martha's Vineyard, and they brought MVSL with them.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] There were also 44 students from around Henniker, New Hampshire, and 27 from the Sandy River valley in Maine, each of which had their own village sign language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Other students brought knowledge of their own home signs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Laurent Clerc, the first teacher at ASD, taught using French Sign Language (LSF), which itself had developed in the Parisian school for the deaf established in 1755.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] From that situation of language contact, a new language emerged, now known as ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] More schools for the deaf were founded after ASD, and knowledge of ASL spread to those schools.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In addition, the rise of deaf community organizations bolstered the continued use of ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Societies such as the National Association of the Deaf and the National Fraternal Society of the Deaf held national conventions that attracted signers from across the country.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] All of that contributed to ASL's wide use over a large geographical area, atypical of a sign language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] While oralism, an approach to educating deaf students focusing on oral language, had previously been used in American schools, the Milan Congress of 1880 made it dominant and effectively banned the use of sign languages at schools in the United States and Europe.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Nevertheless, oralism remained a predominant method of deaf education up to the 1950s.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In response to the Milan Conference, the National Association for the Deaf (NAD) was established.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] As an additional response to the Milan Conference of 1880, the NAD created "Preservation of Sign Language" silent film was made to preserve the language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] These films have been preserved in the US Library of Congress.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In the past, linguists did not consider American Sign Language to be true "language" but as something inferior.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Recognition of the legitimacy of ASL was achieved by William Stokoe, a linguist who arrived at Gallaudet University in 1955 when that was still the dominant assumption.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Aided by the Civil Rights Movement of the 1960s, Stokoe argued for manualism, the use of sign language in deaf education.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Stokoe noted that American Sign Language shares the important features that oral languages have as a means of communication, and even devised a transcription system for ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In doing so, Stokoe revolutionized both deaf education and linguistics.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In the 1960s, ASL was sometimes referred to as "Ameslan", but that term is now considered obsolete.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Counting the number of ASL signers is difficult because ASL users have never been counted by the American census.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] There have been proposals to add ASL as a language people could report they know other than English on the US census, but this was not listed as a language option on the census of 2020.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The ultimate source for current estimates of the number of ASL users in the United States is a report for the National Census of the Deaf Population (NCDP) by Schein and Delk (1974).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Based on a 1972 survey of the NCDP, Schein and Delk provided estimates consistent with a signing population between 250,000 and 500,000.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The survey did not distinguish between ASL and other forms of signing; in fact, the name "ASL" was not yet in widespread use.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Incorrect figures are sometimes cited for the population of ASL users in the United States based on misunderstandings of known statistics.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Demographics of the deaf population have been confused with those of ASL use since adults who become deaf late in life rarely use ASL in the home.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] That accounts for currently-cited estimations that are greater than 500,000; such mistaken estimations can reach as high as 15,000,000.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] A 100,000-person lower bound has been cited for ASL users; the source of that figure is unclear, but it may be an estimate of prelingual deafness, which is when a person is found to have hearing loss prior to acquiring their first language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL is sometimes incorrectly cited as the third- or fourth-most-spoken language in the United States.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Those figures misquote Schein and Delk (1974), who actually concluded that ASL speakers constituted the third-largest population "requiring an interpreter in court".
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Although that would make ASL the third-most used language among monolinguals other than English, it does not imply that it is the fourth-most-spoken language in the United States since speakers of other languages may also speak English.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] That contrasts with Europe, where a variety of sign languages are used within the same continent.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The unique situation of ASL seems to have been caused by the proliferation of ASL through schools influenced by the American School for the Deaf, wherein ASL originated, and the rise of community organizations for the deaf.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Throughout West Africa, ASL-based sign languages are signed by educated deaf adults.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Such languages, imported by boarding schools, are often considered by associations to be the official sign languages of their countries and are named accordingly, such as Nigerian Sign Language and Ghanaian Sign Language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Such signing systems are found in Benin, Burkina Faso, Ivory Coast, Ghana, Liberia, Mauritania, Mali, Nigeria, and Togo.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Due to lack of data, it is still an open question how similar those sign languages are to ASL used in America.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL is also widely learned as a second language for many deaf people in the world.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] American Sign Language production can vary according to location, which is also known as regional variation.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Regional Variation is natural and common among many signed and spoken languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Signers from the American South tend to sign with more flow and ease.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Native signers from New York have been reported as signing comparatively quicker and sharper.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Sign production of native Californian signers has also been reported as being fast.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Research on that phenomenon often concludes that the fast-paced production for signers from the coasts could be due to the fast-paced nature of living in large metropolitan areas.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] That conclusion also supports how the ease with which Southerners sign could be caused by the easygoing environment of the American South in comparison to that of the coasts.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Sign production can also vary depending on age and native language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] For example, sign production of letters may vary in older signers.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Slight differences in fingerspelling production can be a signal of age.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Additionally, signers who learned American Sign Language as a second language vary in production.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] For deaf signers who learned a different sign language before learning American Sign Language, qualities of their native language may show in their ASL production.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Some examples of that varied production include fingerspelling towards the body, instead of away from it, and signing certain movement from bottom to top, instead of top to bottom.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Hearing people who learn American Sign Language also have noticeable differences in signing production.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The most notable production difference of hearing people learning American Sign Language is their rhythm and arm posture.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Most popularly, there are variants of the signs for words such as "birthday", "pizza", "Halloween", "early", and "soon", just a sample of the most commonly recognized signs with variants based on regional change.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The sign for "school" is commonly varied between black and white signers due to previously segregated schools for the deaf.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The rationally segregated schools lead to the development of two separate signed language varieties.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Research is being done to see if Black American Sign Language (BASL) is its own separate language from ASL or a dialect.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Social variation is also found between citation forms and forms used by deaf gay men for words such as "pain" and "protest".
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The prevalence of residential deaf schools can account for the slight regional variance of signs and sign productions across the United States.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Deaf schools often serve students of the state in which the school resides.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] It is hypothesized that because of there being one or only a few deaf residential schools for the deaf, certain variants of a sign prevailed over others due to the choice of variant used by the student of the school/signers in the community.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Prior to the invention of the internet, there was limited access to signers from other regions; however, this has changed with the invention of internet and the ability to view signs online.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] However, American Sign Language does not appear to be vastly varied in comparison to other signed languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Varieties of ASL are found throughout the world.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] There is little difficulty in comprehension among the varieties of the United States and Canada.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] *A Loss for Words: The Story of Deafness in a Family*.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Mutual intelligibility among those ASL varieties is high, and the variation is primarily lexical.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] For example, there are three different words for English *about* in Canadian ASL; the standard way, and two regional variations (Atlantic and Ontario).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Variation may also be phonological, meaning that the same sign may be signed in a different way depending on the region.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] For example, an extremely common type of variation is between the handshapes /1/, /L/, and /5/ in signs with one handshape.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] There is also a distinct variety of ASL used by the Black deaf community.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Black ASL evolved as a result of racially segregated schools in some states, which included the residential schools for the deaf.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Black ASL differs from standard ASL in vocabulary, phonology, and some grammatical structure.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] While African American English (AAE) is generally viewed as more innovating than standard English, Black ASL is more conservative than standard ASL, preserving older forms of many signs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Black sign language speakers use more two-handed signs than in mainstream ASL, are less likely to show assimilatory lowering of signs produced on the forehead (e.g.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Modern Black ASL borrows a number of idioms from AAE; for instance, the AAE idiom "I feel you" is calqued into Black ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL is used internationally as a lingua franca, and a number of closely related sign languages derived from ASL are used in many different countries.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Even so, there have been varying degrees of divergence from standard ASL in those imported ASL varieties.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Bolivian Sign Language is reported to be a dialect of ASL, no more divergent than other acknowledged dialects.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] On the other hand, it is also known that some imported ASL varieties have diverged to the extent of being separate languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] For example, Malaysian Sign Language, which has ASL origins, is no longer mutually comprehensible with ASL and must be considered its own language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] For some imported ASL varieties, such as those used in West Africa, it is still an open question how similar they are to ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] When communicating with hearing English speakers, ASL-speakers often use what is commonly called Pidgin Signed English (PSE) or 'contact signing', a blend of English structure with ASL vocabulary.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] However, there are modes of communication that are not officially a language such as Manual Code of English, such as Pidgin Signed English or Contact Sign, Signing Exact English.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] To codeswitch for not fluent ASL users, some deaf people use some of these modes of communication to help hearing people understand.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Various types of PSE exist, ranging from highly English-influenced PSE (practically relexified English) to PSE which is quite close to ASL lexically and grammatically, but may alter some subtle features of ASL grammar.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Fingerspelling may be used more often in PSE than it is normally used in ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] There have been some constructed sign languages, known as Manually Coded English (MCE), which match English grammar exactly and simply replace spoken words with signs; those systems are not considered to be varieties of ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Tactile ASL (TASL) is a variety of ASL used throughout the United States by and with the DeafBlind.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] It is particularly common among those with Usher's syndrome 1.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] It results in deafness from birth followed by loss of vision later in life; consequently, those with Usher's syndrome 1 often grow up in the deaf community using ASL, and later transition to TASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Usher syndrome 2 is when someone is born with deafness and low vision.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Both types of Usher's Syndrome could result in the DeafBlind person preferring to muse TASL as a method of communication.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] TASL differs from ASL in that signs are produced by touching the palms, and there are some grammatical differences from standard ASL in order to compensate for the lack of nonmanual signing.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL changes over time and from generation to generation.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The sign for telephone has changed as the shape of phones and the manner of holding them have changed.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The development of telephones with screens has also changed ASL, encouraging the use of signs that can be seen on small screens.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In 2013, the White House published a response to a petition that gained over 37,000 signatures to *officially recognize American Sign Language as a community language and a language of instruction in schools*.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The response is titled "there shouldn't be any stigma about American Sign Language" and addressed that ASL is a vital language for the deaf and hard of hearing.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Stigmas associated with sign languages and the use of sign for educating children often lead to the absence of sign during periods in children's lives when they can access languages most effectively.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Benedict advocate not only for bilingualism (using ASL and English training) but also for early childhood intervention for children who are deaf.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] York University psychologist Ellen Bialystok has also campaigned for bilingualism, arguing that those who are bilingual acquire cognitive skills that may help to prevent dementia later in life.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Most children born to deaf parents are hearing and are also known as CODAs ("Children of Deaf Adults").
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Some CODAs acquire ASL as well as deaf cultural values and behaviors from birth from their deaf parents.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Such bilingual hearing children may be mistakenly labeled as being "slow learners" or as having "language difficulties" because of preferential attitudes towards spoken language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Although there is no well-established writing system for ASL, written sign language dates back almost two centuries.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The first systematic writing system for a sign language seems to be that of Roch-Ambroise Auguste Bébian, developed in 1825.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] However, written sign language remained marginal among the public.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In the 1960s, linguist William Stokoe created Stokoe notation specifically for ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] It is alphabetic, with a letter or diacritic for every phonemic (distinctive) hand shape, orientation, motion, and position, though it lacks any representation of facial expression, and is better suited for individual words than for extended passages of text.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Stokoe used that system for his 1965 *A Dictionary of American Sign Language on Linguistic Principles*.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] SignWriting, proposed in 1974 by Valerie Sutton, is the first writing system to gain use among the public and the first writing system for sign languages to be included in the Unicode Standard.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] SignWriting consists of more than 5000 distinct iconic graphs/glyphs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Currently, it is in use in many schools for the deaf, particularly in Brazil, and has been used in International Sign forums with speakers and researchers in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Ethiopia, France, Germany, Italy, Portugal, Saudi Arabia, Slovenia, Tunisia, and the United States.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Sutton SignWriting has both a printed and an electronically produced form so that persons can use the system anywhere that oral languages are written (personal letters, newspapers, and media, academic research).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The systematic examination of the International Sign Writing Alphabet (ISWA) as an equivalent usage structure to the International Phonetic Alphabet for spoken languages has been proposed.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] According to some researchers, SignWriting is not a phonemic orthography and does not have a one-to-one map from phonological forms to written forms.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] That assertion has been disputed, and the process for each country to look at the ISWA and create a phonemic/morphemic assignment of features of each sign language was proposed by researchers Msc.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Roberto Cesar Reis da Costa and Madson Barreto in a thesis forum on June 23, 2014.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The SignWriting community has an open project on Wikimedia Labs to support the various Wikimedia projects on Wikimedia Incubator and elsewhere involving SignWriting.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The ASL Wikipedia request was marked as eligible in 2008 and the test ASL Wikipedia has 50 articles written in ASL using SignWriting.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The most widely used transcription system among academics is HamNoSys, developed at the University of Hamburg.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Based on Stokoe Notation, HamNoSys was expanded to about 200 graphs in order to allow transcription of any sign language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Phonological features are usually indicated with single symbols, though the group of features that make up a handshape is indicated collectively with a symbol.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Several additional candidates for written ASL have appeared over the years, including SignFont, ASL-phabet, and Si5s.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] For English-speaking audiences, ASL is often glossed using English words.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Such glosses are typically all-capitalized and are arranged in ASL order.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] For example, the ASL sentence *DOG NOW CHASE>IX=3 CAT*, meaning "the dog is chasing the cat", uses NOW to mark ASL progressive aspect and shows ASL verbal inflection for the third person (*>IX=3*).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] However, glossing is not used to write the language for speakers of ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Each sign in ASL is composed of a number of distinctive components, generally referred to as parameters.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] All signs can be described using the five parameters involved in signed languages, which are handshape, movement, palm orientation, location and nonmanual markers.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Just as phonemes of sound distinguish meaning in spoken languages, those parameters are the phonemes that distinguish meaning in signed languages like ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] There are also meaningful nonmanual signals in ASL, which may include movement of the eyebrows, the cheeks, the nose, the head, the torso, and the eyes.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] These nonmanual features can indicate grammatical properties of the language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] William Stokoe proposed that such components are analogous to the phonemes of spoken languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] There has also been a proposal that they are analogous to classes like place and manner of articulation.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] As in spoken languages, those phonological units can be split into distinctive features.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] For instance, the handshapes /2/ and /3/ are distinguished by the presence or absence of the feature [± closed thumb], as illustrated to the right.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL has processes of allophony and phonotactic restrictions.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] There is ongoing research into whether ASL has an analog of syllables in spoken language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL has a rich system of verbal inflection, which involves both grammatical aspect: how the action of verbs flows in time—and agreement marking.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Aspect can be marked by changing the manner of movement of the verb; for example, continuous aspect is marked by incorporating rhythmic, circular movement, while punctual aspect is achieved by modifying the sign so that it has a stationary hand position.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Verbs must agree with both the subject and the object, and are marked for number and reciprocity.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Reciprocity is indicated by using two one-handed signs; for example, the sign SHOOT, made with an L-shaped handshape with inward movement of the thumb, inflects to SHOOT[reciprocal], articulated by having two L-shaped hands "shooting" at each other.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL has a productive system of classifiers, which are used to classify objects, their size and shape, and their movement in space.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In the past, classifiers were known as Size and Shape Specifiers (SaSSes).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] For example, a rabbit running downhill would use a classifier consisting of a bent V classifier handshape with a downhill-directed path; if the rabbit is hopping, the path is executed with a bouncy manner.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In general, classifiers are composed of a "classifier handshape" bound to a "movement root".
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The classifier handshape represents the object as a whole, incorporating such attributes as surface, depth, and shape, and is usually very iconic.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The movement root consists of a path, a direction and a manner.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Fingerspelling is a way in which sign languages manually represent the written systems of ambient languages of which they have frequent language contact.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Orthographic symbols of those contact languages are represented through fingerspelling systems in sign languages.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Fingerspelling systems vary cross-linguistically in how they accommodate their ambient written systems, just as much as the written systems vary cross-linguistically themselves.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] For example, in American Sign Language, a one-handed fingerspelled system reflects the symbols of the Roman alphabet which is also used in many other signed languages around the world, mostly in Europe.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In British Sign Language, the fingerspelled symbols represent the Roman alphabet but a two-handed system is used.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In Japan, a one-handed system is used but the symbols represent a syllabary orthographic system.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Fingerspelled words can be used for numerous reasons, including but not limited to: proper nouns, emphasis, representation of loan words etc..
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL is a subject–verb–object (SVO) language, but various phenomena affect that basic word order.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] However, other word orders may also occur since ASL allows the topic of a sentence to be moved to sentence-initial position, a phenomenon known as topicalization.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL also allows null subject sentences whose subject is implied, rather than stated explicitly.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Topicalization, accompanied with a null subject and a subject copy, can produce yet another word order, object–verb–subject (OVS).
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Those properties of ASL allow it a variety of word orders, leading many to question which is the true, underlying, "basic" order.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] There are several other proposals that attempt to account for the flexibility of word order in ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] One proposal is that languages like ASL are best described with a topic–comment structure whose words are ordered by their importance in the sentence, rather than by their syntactic properties.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Another hypothesis is that ASL exhibits free word order, in which syntax is not encoded in word order but can be encoded by other means such as head nods, eyebrow movement, and body position.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] The American with Disabilities Act (ADA) requires public facilities to provide auxiliary aid such as sign language interpreters.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Currently there is a database, the National Registry of Interpreters for the Deaf, to get qualified interpreters.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Sign language interpreters are important for the Deaf and hard-of-hearing community to provide equal access to information in places that may not have written versions like concerts, education, and healthcare.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Not many places have interpreters available on call, with a 50:1 ratio of Deaf or hard-of-hearing person to ASL interpreter.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] This creates barriers for the Deaf community when looking at the social model of disability.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Professional certification can be hard to obtain, and public facilities do not have to provide accommodation if it affects the service or becomes a burden.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Common misconceptions are that signs are iconically self-explanatory, that they are a transparent imitation of what they mean, or even that they are pantomime.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In fact, many signs bear no resemblance to their referent because they were originally arbitrary symbols, or their iconicity has been obscured over time.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Even so, in ASL iconicity plays a significant role; a high percentage of signs resemble their referents in some way.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] That may be because the medium of sign, three-dimensional space, naturally allows more iconicity than oral language.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] In the era of the influential linguist Ferdinand de Saussure, it was assumed that the mapping between form and meaning in language must be completely arbitrary.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Although onomatopoeia is a clear exception, since words like "choo-choo" bear clear resemblance to the sounds that they mimic, the Saussurean approach was to treat them as marginal exceptions.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] ASL, with its significant inventory of iconic signs, directly challenges that theory.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] Research on acquisition of pronouns in ASL has shown that children do not always take advantage of the iconic properties of signs when they interpret their meaning.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] It has been found that when children acquire the pronoun "you", the iconicity of the point (at the child) is often confused, being treated more like a name.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] That is a similar finding to research in oral languages on pronoun acquisition.
[src:burmese-sign-language/asl] It has also been found that iconicity of signs does not affect immediate memory and recall; less iconic signs are remembered just as well as highly-iconic signs.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Its core components are digits, locatives, marks and movements which are written in a fairly rigid order (though in a fairly flexible configuration) from left to right.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The order of the writing is from left to right, top to bottom, with locatives or certain marks often beginning words.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Sentences are ended by the full stop mark ().
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Questions in written ASL are denoted by eyebrow marks bounding the question not unlike Spanish's "¿ ?." Question words or wh-questions in ASL can also form the interrogative.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] There are in total 105 characters in ASLwrite with 67 digits, five diacritic marks, twelve locatives, sixteen extramanual marks and five movement marks.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Since its creation, it has evolved to include more digits, locatives, movements and marks as well as modify those already present.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] si5s, a system built from SignWriting, was first proposed by Robert Arnold in his 2007 Gallaudet thesis *A Proposal of the Written System for ASL*.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The ASLwrite community split from Arnold upon his decision to maintain si5s as a private venture with ASLized after the publication of his and Adrean Clark's book *How to Write American Sign Language*.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Aside from the small, but dedicated, Facebook group of around 470 in July 2023, ASLwrite is rarely used outside such online spaces.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] However, one of the most popular online ASL dictionaries, HandSpeak, has begun to incorporate ASLwrite as the primary written component of ASL definitions.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] ASLwrite is a somacheirographic system meaning that it represents the body (Greek: σῶμα *sôma* 'body') and hands (Greek: χείρ *kheír* 'hand') and relays phonemic information.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] However, it also incorporates logographs (questioning marks) and is featural.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The general principle is to capture a single ASL word per segment, from left to right, registering non-manual feature(s), location(s), handshape(s), movement(s) and general orientation.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] It imagines the writer/speaker is looking down at their hands or viewing words from the profile such that words can be made either as if seen from straight-on or from one's profile.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet captures handshape information as well as orientation, movement and some locations.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Locatives are characters that capture location, though handshape diacritics like *edge* do capture some locations such as edge of palm.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Diacritics, such as movements, modify handshapes and can indicate small movements or small orientations.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements themselves are fairly flexible in their shapes and orientations, which makes digitising this script difficult.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Frontal or profile locatives – Captures the same location information, just from two perspectives.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] An example (seen on the right) is the shoulder locative is either a shoulder frontal locative that is written above or below the handshape(s).
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Handshapes – Can be written before or after the locative.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] A handshape can be oriented in 360° depending on its location and is written at the end of its movement path if there is one.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Each handshape present is written, and when more than one handshape (of one hand) is written, a movement must be present.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements – Larger movements or movements that affect multiple handshapes.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] When a handshape changes without overt movement, the handshapes are written left-to-right with a single movement below, similar to an underline.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual & punctuation marks – These are questioning marks such as *why*, *who*, *how* and *how*.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet is composed of handshapes called digits that are modified by diacritics and movements.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] It shares 23 handshapes with ASL's manual alphabet.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Digits are grouped together by features such as +thumb/-thumb or +closed/-closed.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] In practise, there are 67 digits in ASLwrite's digibet, though that number is growing as new digits are added representing diverse handshapes.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Moreover, other languages may adopt this system which would add increasingly more digits.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] There are five diacritics, of which one is a movement diacritic.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements are flexible and thus hard to capture in a digital or non-handwritten fashion.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The movements are diverse and aim to capture the movements of the hands, arms and body.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] There are three points – an **endpoint**, a **firmpoint** and a **contactpoint** –, an **orbit mark**, a **steering** and a **crank mark** as well as the movement mark or line.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The movement line follows the path of the hand(s) and can be as clean (e.g., – or | ) or as erratic as possible.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The points denote the end of a handshape's path and the degree to which the motion is made.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] A contactpoint denotes an imaginary or in-the-air point with the contactpoint ending at a location and noted as being a firm ending with the firmpoint.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The orbit mark indicates a central "point" around which the handshapes orbit; for orbital paths cut short, one would use a steering mark, and for parallel cranking motions, the crank mark would be used.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The locatives are characters that denote a specific location on or near the signer's body.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] They are presented from a face-on and side-view.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The two sub-classifications are **frontal** and **profile locatives**.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual marks vary quite significantly and can only be placed at the beginning or end of words or phrases.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] **Eyebrow marks** are denoted before and after the word(s) in question thus bounding the words that are modified by eyebrow marks.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] They are called: **Raised (), Knit, Wan, Slanted** and **Squint**.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Questioning marks exist in ASL as logographs that denote ASL's wh-questions such as WHO or FOR-FOR.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] They are placed after a closed word's or phrase's second eyebrow mark and can exist as an entire sentence alone.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Mouth marks are characters that relay what action the mouth is doing.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] It is placed inside the first eyebrow mark.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Body movements are non-manual, non-facial features such as **shoulder shift ()** or **head nod**.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] They, as well as **nose crinkle ()**, stand alone and can be inserted anywhere, inside and outside of eyebrow-marked phrases.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] means *Yes?* in ASL composed of , , and where the raised eyebrow marks at the beginning and the end indicate it is a yes/no question, and the hinge mark () denotes that the S handshape digit () makes a nodding motion.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The circular point at the end is a full stop mark indicating the end of the sentence.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Unlike in English writing, the full stop mark () is employed for all sentences, even questions (as seen here).
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Breaks in the sentence, as seen below, are denoted by the shoulder shift mark ().
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The text on the right is from Chapters 1:2–4 of the Book of Ruth.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] The first quoted text is the verse in English and the second is an ASL gloss.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] Due to the complexity of the writing system and its need for flexibility for movements, it means that producing anything in a digital format is difficult.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] However, there are efforts to create fonts headed by members of its Facebook group, notably looking at proper font creation and using current keyboard characters such as ' } ' or ' _.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] ' to achieve minor forms of communication in ASL over text.
[src:burmese-sign-language/aslwrite] An example phrase is " }_.U- " which means 'thank you' in ASL.
[src:burmese-sign-language/burmese-sign-language] There are one or two known sign languages in Myanmar (Burma).
[src:burmese-sign-language/burmese-sign-language] There are three schools for the deaf in the country: the Mary Chapman School for the Deaf in Yangon (est.
[src:burmese-sign-language/burmese-sign-language] 1904), the School for the Deaf, Mandalay (est.
[src:burmese-sign-language/burmese-sign-language] 1964), and the Immanuel School for the Deaf in Kalay (est.
[src:burmese-sign-language/burmese-sign-language] At least in Yangon, instruction in oral, in the Burmese language, with sign used to support it.
[src:burmese-sign-language/burmese-sign-language] The sign of Yangon and Mandalay is different, but it is not clear if they are one language or two.
[src:burmese-sign-language/burmese-sign-language] Influences on the language(s) include ASL in all schools, as well as Korean Sign Language, Australian Sign Language, Thai Sign Language, and possibly a local substratum.
[src:burmese-sign-language/burmese-sign-language] A government project was set up in 2010 to establish a national sign language with the aid of the Japanese Federation of the Deaf.
[src:burmese-sign-language/burmese-sign-language] Two manual alphabets are in use in Yangon: the American manual alphabet, which may or may not be well known, and a Burmese-based alphabet taught during the 1970s and 1980s.
